text: I suspect that Hugh Lofting just might not be impressed with this offering. I greatly enjoy watching Robert Downey, Jr. and admire him, but I wish Disney would have tried to at least act a little like they were actually going to follow this great author`s work with at least some resemblance to his narratives. Well, its Disney, after all, and if they cannot beat U they will buy U out, or change the story`s characters etc. I`m sure I will see this movie, but if anyone reading this wants to know the true Dr. Doolittle, I encourage the reading of Hugh Lofting`s books; for a child they are all of wonder and for an adult they are a gift of what it was like to have a child`s innocence. This movie looks to have lots of bells and whistles and it should entertain, as Mr. Downey is always tops, but it just isn`t the real Puddleby On The Marsh. :)

text: Why that song? God I hope that they don't shove that song down the audience throat's during the film. Having read all the books and knowing the characters... half of those animals were nowhere in the Voyages. Who is the little girl? Why is there a gorilla? Is that Cheechee? The Chimpanzee? Seriously.   I just hope that they go with the 'educated man learns animal languages individually by species' plot and not the 'I woke up and they all talked' version.   And they are horribly smooshing multiple books worth of plots into this.   Damnit, is it too much to ask for a book accurate adaptation of the series for freaking once?!?   Hoping that there's no oc sue love interest like in the Rex Harrison version. That was the only true problem in that movie. The Eddie Murphy version was a travesty to the name dolittle.   I was hoping to avoid the human speech from the animals thing too. But I figured that was a doomed cause the day I saw the cast list.   Will wait and see about this film. I have dashed hopes from this trailer. I hope that the environazis have not gotten a hold of the script. I will be pissed if it is full of save the environment garbage. I seriously do not need pandering to in that regard, and it will fall on the deaf ears of those that only listen to profit margins.   Please keep politics out of Dr. Dolittle.   And don't make him a vegitarian. He was not one in the books.

text: Forget the 90s-2000s Dr Dolittle, those movies were just complete spoofs of what Dolittle truly was about. This is far more based on the books, and so was the original 1960s one. He had real African voyages, explored deeper issues with animals and dealing with them. Whatever the 90s-2000s were are just cliched Eddie Murphy (or family legacy) shenanigans featuring animals and someone called Dr Dolittle who lived a stereotypical suburban life in the U.S pandering to the Hollywood fantasy. It's like telling someone you are Batman, but you are just Batman in a costume stopping school bullies or something or dealing with some dodgy movie agent rather than real criminals.

text: Downey is a good actor, don't get me wrong, but who else was watching this trailer and thinking to them self "This is so a role for Johnny Depp.."? The guy just has that swagger that makes him so perfect for the role of an eccentric individual. A great actor can fit multiple roles, but imho the best actors to watch are the ones that naturally fit the roles that they're placed in.   I learned this many years ago while watching movies with John Candy. Sure they could have placed that guy in movies where he was some asshole billionaire, or evil mastermind, and he may have done well in such roles via acting skills, but the majority of the movies he was placed in, he was this big, jolly happy go lucky individual. He did great in those roles because that's the kind of person that he was in real life. The best way to explain this is that the best lies are those spliced with truths (how else do you make billions of people believe there's a magic man in the sky watching our every move like some all powerful santa clause?).
